% Automatisch generiert — Thema: School Uniforms
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro82).  % [pro] Uniforms help troubled students feel that troubled students have the support of a community.
arg(pro15).  % [pro] When students are dressed alike, students are safer.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] Students dressed in uniform are better perceived by teachers and peers.
arg(pro95).  % [pro] Former US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, when she was a 2008 US presidential candidate, advocated school uniforms as a way to help students focus on learning, saying “Take clothing choices off the table and put the focus on school, not on what students are wearing.”
arg(pro36).  % [pro] Uniforms provide less distraction, according to Chris Hammons, principal of Woodland Middle School in Coeur d'Alene, ID.
arg(pro36b).  % [pro] Uniforms provide less drama, according to Chris Hammons, principal of Woodland Middle School in Coeur d'Alene, ID.
arg(pro36c).  % [pro] Uniforms increase focus on learning, according to Chris Hammons, principal of Woodland Middle School in Coeur d'Alene, ID.
arg(pro32).  % [pro] It is very important that girls do not have to give in to these sorts of pressures.
arg(pro32b).  % [pro] Girls actually welcome wearing a uniform.
arg(pro29).  % [pro] If someone were to come into a building, the intruder could easily be recognized.
arg(con36).  % [con] An ugly uniform shows that the issue is not just about the individual.
arg(con27).  % [con] The school uniform policy broke the guarantee of a free public education and violated Laura and Scott Bell's children's right to freedom of expression.
arg(con27b).  % [con] Laura and Scott Bell said they were required to pay $641 for their children’s uniforms in August 2007.
arg(con140).  % [con] Most public schools with uniform policies are in poor neighborhoods.
arg(con140b).  % [con] Uniform policies emphasize the class distinctions that uniforms were supposed to eliminate.
arg(con23).  % [con] The paper entitled “Public School Uniforms: Effect on Perceptions of Gang Presence, School Climate, and Student Self-Perceptions” shows that students who are not required to wear school uniforms demonstrated higher self-perception scores.
arg(con109).  % [con] Serious discipline and academic issues are unlikely to be solved by nostalgically resurrecting the blazer.
arg(con109b).  % [con] Serious discipline and academic issues are unlikely to be solved by draconian decrees issued from the headmaster's study regarding skirt length.
arg(con9).  % [con] Students' transition towards adulthood can be hindered by uniforms.
arg(con8).  % [con] There are limited choices for males.
arg(con8b).  % [con] There are limited choices for females.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con27, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The con claim that uniforms violate freedom of expression attacks the legitimacy premise underlying the pro’s benefit claim.
att(con140b, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Arguing that uniforms emphasize class distinctions directly attacks the premise that they foster community support.
att(pro82, con23).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — The study showing higher self‑perception without uniforms contradicts the pro’s claim that uniforms improve students’ sense of support.
att(con109, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The claim that blazers won’t solve discipline issues attacks the premise that uniforms help troubled students feel supported.
att(con109b, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Saying skirt‑length decrees won’t solve problems undermines the premise that any uniform element provides community support.
att(con27, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The freedom‑of‑expression objection attacks the premise that uniform policies are acceptable, undermining the safety argument
att(con109, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=82 — The claim that blazers won’t solve discipline challenges attacks the premise that uniforms make students safer.
att(con109b, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Arguing that strict skirt‑length rules won’t solve discipline problems undermines the safety premise of uniforms.
att(con36, pro4).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B attacks the premise that uniforms improve perception by highlighting that an ugly uniform can create negative impressions
att(con27, pro4).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B challenges the underlying premise of A by arguing that uniforms violate freedom of expression
att(con140b, pro4).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B claims uniforms highlight class differences, challenging the premise that uniforms improve perception.
att(con23, pro4).  % [undercutting] conf=85 — B presents evidence that non‑uniformed students have higher self‑perception, showing A's conclusion does not follow.
att(con36, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=85 — Claims an ugly uniform draws attention, challenging the premise that uniforms remove clothing focus.
att(con27, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=90 — Argues uniforms violate freedom of expression, attacking the premise that they are a permissible policy.
att(con27b, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Points out high cost, undermining the premise that uniforms are beneficial overall.
att(con140, pro95).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — Shows uniform policies are concentrated in poor neighborhoods, questioning the link to learning focus.
att(con140b, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=80 — States uniforms emphasize class distinctions, contradicting the premise that they level clothing differences.
att(con23, pro95).  % [undercutting] conf=85 — Cites study where non‑uniform students have higher self‑perception, weakening the claim that uniforms improve outcomes.
att(con109, pro95).  % [rebuttal] conf=95 — Asserts uniforms will not solve discipline or academic problems, directly opposing the claim they aid learning.
att(pro95, con109b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Pro claims uniforms improve focus while con says such decrees won’t solve academic issues, making the conclusions mutually exclusive.
att(con36, pro36b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The con claim attacks the premise that uniforms are beneficial by arguing that an ugly uniform shows the issue is not merely individual.
